def displot(data, title, num=1,bins=[30]):
    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    f, ax = plt.subplots(1,num, figsize=(10,5))

    if num==1:
        
        sns.distplot(data, bins=bins[0])
    else:
        for i,d in enumerate(data):
            sns.distplot(d, bins=bins[i], ax=ax[i])
    plt.title(title)
    plt.ylabel('Density')

def cplot(data, num=1, size=7):
    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    f, ax = plt.subplots(1,num, figsize=(size*num,6))

    if num==1:
        
        sns.countplot(data, order=data.value_counts().sort_values(ascending=False).index, palette='viridis')
    else:
        for i,d in enumerate(data):
            sns.countplot(d, order=d.value_counts().sort_values(ascending=False).index, palette='viridis', ax=ax[i])
    plt.tight_layout()

def highlight_max(s):
    '''
    highlight the maximum in a Series.
    '''
    is_max = s == s.max()
    return ['background-color: darkorange' if v else '' for v in is_max]

In [406]:
def cramers_v(confusion_matrix):
    """ calculate Cramers V statistic for categorial-categorial association.
        uses correction from Bergsma and Wicher,
        Journal of the Korean Statistical Society 42 (2013): 323-328
    """
    chi2, p, dof, _  = ss.chi2_contingency(confusion_matrix)
    n = confusion_matrix.sum()
    phi2 = chi2 / n
    r, k = confusion_matrix.shape
    phi2corr = max(0, phi2 - ((k-1)*(r-1))/(n-1))
    rcorr = r - ((r-1)**2)/(n-1)
    kcorr = k - ((k-1)**2)/(n-1)
    return (np.sqrt(phi2corr / min((kcorr-1), (rcorr-1))), p, dof)

V = []
for cat1 in cat_col:
    for cat2 in cat_col:
        ct = pd.crosstab(dft[cat1], dft[cat2], normalize='index').mul(100).round(0)
        if cat1 == 'Class Name' or (cat2== 'Class Name'):
            v, _, _ = cramers_v(ct.values+0.1) ## since empty rows and columns result in error (division by 0)
        else:
            v, _, _ = cramers_v(ct.values)
        V.append(v)

Even if we have good r2 value with statisitical significance (low P), we need to check if the regression meets the assumption. The bottom table shows some metrics that can be used to check if it meets the assumption.

Omnibus:¶

It's basically ANOVA, it tests the data as a whole. We can test the homegenity of Variance. P-value is quite signifcant at 0.

Skew and Kurtosis:¶

Normal distribution has a skew of zero and kurtosis of 3. The rule of thumb seems to be:

  • If the skewness is between -0.5 and 0.5, the data are fairly symmetrical.
  • If the skewness is between -1 and -0.5(negatively skewed) or between 0.5 and 1(positively skewed), the data are moderately skewed.
  • If the skewness is less than -1(negatively skewed) or greater than 1(positively skewed), the data are highly skewed.

Kurtosis shows the outliers, data set is an indicator that data has heavy tails or outliers.

Durban-Watson:¶

Measure of autocorrelation usually for time series.

Jarque-Bera:¶

Test for normality. In general, a large J-B value indicates that errors are not normally distributed.

Cond. No:¶

A test for multicollinearity (if in a fit with multiple parameters, the parameters are related with each other).

The intercept group is the General category group since the General group’s data was not included in the model’s formula. Their data is still captured because this group has values of 0 in both of the other groups.

Overall the model is significant with F = 19.92 and P much less than 0.01. This tells there is significant difference in group means. The coefficients (coef in the table), are the difference in mean between the control group and the respective group listed.

The bottom of the table there are a few tests that were conducted to test the models’s assumptions.

The Durban-Watson tests is to detect the presence of autocorrelation, Jarque-Bera tests the assumption of normality, Omnibus tests the assumption of homogeneity of variance, and the Condition Number (condno) assess multicollinearity. Condition Number values over 20 are indicative of multicollinearity.

def percentagebarplot(x, y, hue, data, ax=None, n=5):
    sns.barplot(x =x, y =y, hue=hue,\
                data = data[[x, hue]]\
                .reset_index(drop=True)\
                .groupby([x])[hue]\
                .value_counts(normalize=True)\
                .rename('Percentage').mul(100)\
                .reset_index()\
                .sort_values(hue),\
                palette=sns.diverging_palette(240, 10, n=n, center="light"),\
               ax =ax)

def cleanText(text):
    
    #Remove non-alpha characters
    text = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z0-9 ]', '',text)
    #Remove multiple spaces, replace by single space
    text = re.sub(r'  +', ' ', text)
    #Lower case all 
    text = text.lower()
    
    return text

Difference in token length through nltk and manually. It appears that manual "tokens" are more in number when compared to nltk generated tokens. After comparing the two above it's seen that nltk word tokenizer does not process the words "gonna, gotta, cannot, wanna, cannot" etc correctly and breaks each into two tokens. This however should lead to more token with nltk, opposite to what we are seeing here. Basically when token is split it generates more stop words like "not", "can", "Can" etc. which are removed hence resulting in fewer tokens.

However difference in unique tokens is not too much (4) and we can use either of the tokens. Lets use

def Lemma(tokens):
    lemma = WordNetLemmatizer()
    lemma_sent = []
    
    for word, tag in pos_tag(tokens):
        if tag.startswith('NN'):
            pos= 'n'
        elif tag.startswith('VB'):
            pos= 'v'
        else:
            pos = 'a'
        lemma_sent.append(lemma.lemmatize(word, pos))
    
    return lemma_sent

                  background_color=color,

Naive Byes Classifier¶

In [23]:
# already created sorted freq distribution of tokens  "items"

featLab = list(zip(dft['Clean Tokens'], dft['Recommended IND']))

word_features = list(dict(items).keys())[:2000]

def find_features(doc):
    
    ## For each review, create a feature dictionary recording which features are present and not. 
    ## for example first review has these features ['absolutely', 'wonderful', 'silky', 'sexy', 'comfortable']
    ## only these will be True reset all False. 
    
    words = set(doc)
    features = {}
    for w in word_features:
         features[w] = (w in words)
    return features

featureset = [(find_features(txt), label ) for  (txt, label) in featLab]
